Research questions:
RQ1: How do ARIMA, Prophet, and LSTM-Autoencoder compare in anomaly detection accuracy and inference latency when deployed in a production MLOps pipeline?
RQ2: How effectively does automated drift detection (using PSI and KL Divergence) identify distribution shifts in time series data, and how does drift-triggered retraining compare to periodic retraining in maintaining model performance?
RQ3: What is the overhead (latency, throughput, resource cost) introduced by adding a full monitoring stack (Prometheus + Grafana + Evidently) to a time series anomaly detection service?

Dataset:
NAB (Numenta Anomaly Benchmark). Free, labeled, real-world time series, widely cited in the papers you're using. 
github.com/numenta/NAB. Has multiple sub-datasets (CPU usage, traffic, Twitter, AWS metrics)
realKnownCause gives you ground truth labels with documented causes — you can cite why an anomaly happened, which strengthens your experimental write-up. 
realAWSCloudwatch mirrors a real production MLOps environment, directly tying your dataset choice to your research context. 
artificialWithAnomaly lets you inject controlled drift for your RQ2 experiments, since you can shift the anomaly pattern and verify your detection pipeline catches it.

